WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.519
Yes, good morning. Yeah, good morning. Now, we've got 10 minutes for 10.

2
00:00:13.519 --> 00:00:23.559
Okay, so we start, right? Yes, please. Okay, so, Kia ora, everybody. My name is Cosmo Geoffrey.

3
00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:29.719
I'm currently the President of the Hantemri Howard League for Penal Reform, and with me today

4
00:00:29.719 --> 00:00:36.679
is Buster Thompson, our Secretary. As we stated in our written submission, the Howard League has been

5
00:00:36.679 --> 00:00:43.799
advocating for penal reform for over 100 years. While we primarily engage in advocating for reform

6
00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:50.920
related to prisons, we also pride ourselves on promoting an evidence-based consideration

7
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.120
of all proposed legislation that relates to justice and civil liberty. We are aware that there are

8
00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:04.120
other organisations who provided much more detailed submissions on this topic. The Howard

9
00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:10.520
League would like to support those organisations in submitting that we impose the needless expansion

10
00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:16.920
of police powers. We believe we should be strengthening privacy laws rather than weakening

11
00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:23.480
them. More especially, when it was revealed that over 50% of those images taken by the police

12
00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:32.680
were persons of Maori and Pacifica descent. As an organisation, the Howard League is confronted

13
00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:39.560
daily by the inherent discrimination that is rife within our justice system. Polynesian and Maori

14
00:01:39.560 --> 00:01:47.560
people are totally over-represented in all the cohorts we advocate for the New Zealand justice

15
00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:55.719
system. And the police are no exception. More Maori and Pacifica people are stopped, apprehended,

16
00:01:55.719 --> 00:02:02.599
arrested, tried in our courts, and imprisoned by a factor of at least three times compared to

17
00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:11.800
Pacifica subjects. Considering the disproportionate impact this will have on Maori, we think that

18
00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:18.760
more effort is required to work with Maori and Maori organisations in developing legislation

19
00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:26.439
related to the collection and storage of information. Consequently, the Howard League urges

20
00:02:26.439 --> 00:02:33.319
the Justice Committee to take a breath and consider fully the implications of this legislation.

21
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:43.240
In preparing our submission, we basically decided that it's easy to criticise, anyone can criticise,

22
00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:49.560
but what we want to do is try and provide some answers. So we researched what other European

23
00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:57.719
jurisdictions do in basically managing public surveillance and storage of collected data.

24
00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:05.479
And what we found was really interesting. Most of the countries in the European Union have signed

25
00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:13.719
up, in fact all of them as far as we can work out have signed up to the GDPR. I didn't know what

26
00:03:13.719 --> 00:03:20.840
this was either, but it's the General Data Protection Regulation. So they all sign up to the General Data

27
00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:27.800
Protection Regulation and this sets strict regulations which control the surveillance

28
00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:34.919
and storage of people in public places. For example, there's a proportionality requirement.

29
00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:43.400
Police cannot indiscriminately photograph the entire population. The collection of biometric

30
00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:51.080
data is prohibited in principle, but if permitted, if it's strictly necessary,

31
00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:58.120
it must be proportionate for investigating specific crimes or maintaining security.

32
00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:06.200
The storage and retirement. The EU allows the retention of biometric data of suspects and

33
00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:14.040
convicts, but national laws must set appropriate time limits for the reviewing and the need to

34
00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:21.080
store that data. For example, in most European countries, if any of the people whose images

35
00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:27.640
are taken and stored do not offend in the next 12 months, that data is deleted. And that's what

36
00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:34.280
we believe should happen in New Zealand. We could outline this in much greater detail,

37
00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:42.440
but to be truthful, the Parliamentary Committee, the Justice Committee and you guys generally

38
00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:49.800
have much more efficient and capable research people who can provide this information. We don't

39
00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:58.840
need to reinvent the wheel. There are basically instructions and institutions in place that deal

40
00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:06.600
this sort of thing. Why should we be starting out from scratch and having a carte blanche system

41
00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:17.720
where people can be willingly recorded and data stored infinitely? We believe that a body such

42
00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:25.320
as the Privacy Commissioner should be set up to oversee this legislation and be responsible

43
00:05:26.279 --> 00:05:32.680
for the taking and storage of images in the public. If those people do not offend for the

44
00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:40.120
next 12 months, then that data should be deleted. That makes sense. There needs to be a clear purpose

45
00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:47.719
for why police are taking photos of someone rather than a vague possible future purpose.

46
00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:55.320
Otherwise, effectively, anyone's photo can be taken by the police indiscriminately and stored forever.

47
00:05:55.960 --> 00:06:03.080
We believe this not to be a fair and reasonable situation and we want it to be controlled.

48
00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:11.640
That's our oral submission and we could answer any questions if there were any.

49
00:06:11.719 --> 00:06:14.279
Hey Bill, thank you very much. Hon Dr Duncan Webb.

50
00:06:15.399 --> 00:06:19.319
Kia ora Cosmo and Buster. Thanks for all the work that you do.

51
00:06:20.279 --> 00:06:27.000
Look, I guess most people would accept that if a police are investigating a crime or

52
00:06:27.879 --> 00:06:32.519
something they know as planned as a crime that surveillance and photographs is probably just

53
00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:40.279
ifiable. Do you have any comments on them taking photographs where they are really just

54
00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:46.440
gathering information about the behaviours of people that they know are part of criminal networks

55
00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.640
rather than investigating a particular crime or proposed crime?

56
00:06:54.360 --> 00:07:00.520
Well, our view is that, guys, it should be for a particular purpose in that it should be to

57
00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:06.040
investigate a crime rather than just otherwise you get this risk of investigating people who

58
00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:12.280
they consider associates but are not actually committing any offences. I think it goes too far

59
00:07:12.280 --> 00:07:17.240
to be investigating or taking photos of this biometric information of people who are not

60
00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:23.560
actively involved in a crime. Thanks, Bill. Just personally, I don't know if this helps, but

61
00:07:24.439 --> 00:07:30.920
it's no secret that I have been in prison. It was over 25 years ago. I was down in Twizel

62
00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:37.640
the other day and I got stopped by the police on my jocati and he asked my license. Within seconds,

63
00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:42.600
he brought up my history, started talking about something that happened 25 years ago,

64
00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:50.360
and I was left standing there wondering, haven't I done time? Shouldn't I be allowed to get on

65
00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:56.759
with my life? And I'm just wary of collecting information on people that can be called up

66
00:07:56.759 --> 00:08:04.920
within seconds and used against them when it doesn't relate to the whole idea of taking images of people.

67
00:08:06.599 --> 00:08:11.959
All right. Well, thank you for sharing that, particularly that your last personal comment,

68
00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:17.959
which was very interesting. And both of you this morning joining us on this submission. So,

69
00:08:17.959 --> 00:08:23.959
thanks for your time. Right, now we're going to go to the news. No other questions I take it?

70
00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:30.360
No. Yeah. Thank you. Thank you very much, Cosmo. Right, we're going to go to the

